{"type":"message","id":"7d963985","parentId":"cc0f5591","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:04:41.521Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The default gateway is 172.23.96.1, which is the WSL host adapter address. But that's the internal WSL network gateway, not the Windows machine's external IP on the LAN.\n\nI need to find the actual IP of the Windows machine on the local network. Let me try to scan or guess - in WSL2, the Windows host is usually accessible via the gateway address, but for external LAN access I need the actual LAN IP.\n\nActually wait - in WSL2, the networking works differently. The Windows host is accessible via the gateway IP (172.23.96.1), but for port forwarding from Windows to WSL, Windows uses the external LAN IP or the \"vEthernet (WSL)\" adapter IP.\n\nLet me try a different approach - run a simple HTTP server on Windows and see if I can reach it from WSL. Or better yet, let me just try to curl the port proxy port.\n\nActually, the portproxy I set up should listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0) on port 19222, and forward to 127.0.0.1:9222. So if I can reach the Windows host from WSL, I should be able to use port 19222.\n\nThe issue is - what IP do I use to reach the Windows host? It's not 172.23.96.1 (that's just the WSL virtual switch gateway). The Windows host has an IP on the LAN. Let me check if there's a way to find it.\n\nActually in WSL2, typically you reach the Windows host via the gateway IP for port forwarding purposes. But for the netsh portproxy to work with external machines, it would need to listen on the actual LAN IP.\n\nWait - I set up portproxy with listenaddress=0.0.0.0, so it should listen on all Windows IP addresses. But the question is whether WSL can reach the Windows host at all for this purpose.\n\nLet me try pinging the gateway and also try to directly curl the port.","thinkingSignature":"58cda6003048ed52796bb7bb15b508a9840732ba130c220b5aef7df43dfa3f07"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_s1ub52flsbvk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ping -c 1 172.23.96.1 2>/dev/null | head -3 && curl -s --max-time 5 http://172.23.96.1:19222/json/version 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":42499,"output":497,"cacheRead":20080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":63076,"cost":{"input":0.0127497,"output":0.0005964,"cacheRead":0.0012047999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.014550899999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776236665127,"responseId":"062e6b78e008f31223c85ffad986f373"}}
{"type":"message","id":"db1e21ea","parentId":"7d963985","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:04:46.591Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_s1ub52flsbvk_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"PING 172.23.96.1 (172.23.96.1) 56(84) bytes of data.\n64 bytes from 172.23.96.1: icmp_seq=1 ttl=128 time=0.497 ms\n\n(Command exited with code 28)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":28,"durationMs":5023,"aggregated":"PING 172.23.96.1 (172.23.96.1) 56(84) bytes of data.\n64 bytes from 172.23.96.1: icmp_seq=1 ttl=128 time=0.497 ms\n\n(Command exited with code 28)","cwd":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776236686582}}
{"type":"message","id":"eb3456fe","parentId":"db1e21ea","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:05:02.140Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ping works, but curl to port 19222 failed (exit code 28 - timeout). The portproxy might not be working as expected, or the Windows firewall is blocking it.\n\nLet me try a different approach - maybe I should check if the portproxy was actually set up correctly. Or try using a different method.\n\nWait - actually, the issue might be that in WSL2, the networking is NAT'd through the Windows host, but for incoming connections to Windows, WSL is on a separate network. The portproxy on Windows with listenaddress=0.0.0.0 should listen on all interfaces, but maybe the Windows firewall is blocking it.\n\nLet me try a simpler test first - just try to curl any port on the Windows host to see if basic connectivity works.\n\nActually, thinking about it more - the portproxy command sets up a port forward from Windows port 19222 to 127.0.0.1:9222. But from WSL's perspective, when I try to connect to 172.23.96.1:19222, the traffic goes:\n1. WSL sends to gateway 172.23.96.1\n2. Windows receives on its network interface\n3. Windows portproxy should forward to localhost:9222\n\nBut the issue might be that 172.23.96.1 is the internal WSL adapter IP, not the main LAN adapter IP of Windows. So the traffic might not be going where we think.\n\nLet me try another approach - ask Windows for its actual LAN IP and try connecting that way.\n\nOr actually, maybe I should just try to communicate through the Windows host's external IP. In WSL2, typically you can reach the Windows host via the \"vEthernet (WSL)\" adapter's IP, or through the network bridge.\n\nLet me try to see what IPs Windows has.","thinkingSignature":"4f17d6f7902535ebffe993f0566863359623010a57134b67d3edcaa51b6eae69"},{"type":"text","text":"ping 通但连不上端口。可能是防火墙。试试这个 — 在**管理员权限的 CMD** 关掉防火墙测试：\n\n```\nnetsh advfirewall set allprofiles state off\n```\n\n如果不敢关防火墙，换这个检查命令：\n\n```\nnetsh interface portproxy show all\n```\n\n看看 portproxy 有没有设置上。"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43072,"output":451,"cacheRead":20080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":63603,"cost":{"input":0.0129216,"output":0.0005411999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0012047999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0146676}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776236686595,"responseId":"062e6b8dc1fc2f61590412143edf7667"}}
